text: TUNISIA’S GENDER EQUALITY LANDSCAPE
label: H2

text: COUNTRY DEVELOPMENT CONTEXT
label: H3

text: At the time of writing, Tunisia continues to face a deli-
label: BODY

text: cate political and economic moment. Hopes were high
label: BODY

text: for human rights and gender equality after Tunisia’s
label: BODY

text: democratic transition ignited the 2011 revolution in the
label: BODY

text: region. However, the foundation of new institutions and
label: BODY

text: norms for the country has been undercut by limited social
label: BODY

text: dialogue and economic struggles, exacerbated by the
label: BODY

text: COVID-19 pandemic. Some optimism followed the 2019
label: BODY

text: elections, but since then concerns have deepened due to
label: BODY

text: the slow response to economic challenges and the revela-
label: BODY

text: tion of deep political cleavages. The President suspended
label: BODY

text: parliament in July 2021, paving the way for parliamentary
label: BODY

text: elections in December 2023. In July 2022, a public refer-
label: BODY

text: endum led to the adoption of a new constitution. The
label: BODY

text: President’s appointment of a woman as head of govern-
label: BODY

text: ment in 2021 – the first ever in the region – was welcomed
label: BODY

text: as a positive step. But other signals, such as the President’s
label: BODY

text: dissolution of all municipal councils in March 2023, put
label: BODY

text: into question how recent political shifts will translate to
label: BODY

text: safeguarding individual and public freedoms and address-
label: BODY

text: ing the country’s pressing social and economic hardships.
label: BODY

text: GENDER EQUALITY SNAPSHOT
label: H3

text: The Convention to End Discrimination Against Women (CEDAW) was ratified by Tunisia in 1985; reservations were lifted 2011 but the lifting
label: BODY

text: was formally registered in 2014 with notification by the Government to the UN.
label: BODY

text: The National Action Plan was approved by Tunisia’s Ministerial Council on 8 October 2018.
label: BODY

text: Following the 2011 uprisings, Tunisia promulgated a new
label: BODY

text: constitution in 2014 that enshrined equality between
label: BODY

text: women and men, transparency, inclusion, parity and
label: BODY

text: non-discrimination, and explicitly addressed ending
label: BODY

text: violence against women (EVAW). This led to advances in
label: BODY

text: governance, political and human rights, and social reform
label: BODY

text: that favoured gender equality, specifically the passage of
label: BODY

text: two laws, one on EVAW and another on gender-sensitive
label: BODY

text: budgeting. The new constitution adopted in July 2022,
label: BODY

text: criticized by some for expanding presidential powers, rein-
label: BODY

text: forces these same rights of non-discrimination that are the
label: BODY

text: foundation for advancing gender equality. Since 2014, the
label: BODY

text: country has hosted six consecutive free and fair elections,
label: BODY

text: including the recent parliamentary elections in 2022-2023.
label: BODY

text: The impressive gains women made in representation at
label: BODY

text: the local level – primarily due to the 2018 elections that
label: BODY

text: saw unprecedented participation and resulted in women
label: BODY

text: winning 47 per cent of local council positions – were largely
label: BODY

text: lost upon the president’s dissolution of municipal councils
label: BODY

text: in March 2023 and the amendment of the electoral law.
label: BODY

text: Tunisia’s commitment to women’s rights is evident in its
label: BODY

text: ratification of the Convention on the Elimination of All
label: BODY

text: Forms of Discrimination Against Women (CEDAW) in 1985,
label: BODY

text: and lifting of all reservations in 2014. 1 The government also
label: BODY

text: aligned its national Development Plan 2016-2020 with
label: BODY

text: the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) of the UN’s
label: BODY

text: Agenda 2030, and issued its second Voluntary National
label: BODY

text: Review on SDG implementation in 2021, which positioned
label: BODY

text: gender equality as a top priority. Additionally, the adoption
label: BODY

text: of Tunisia’s first National Action Plan (NAP) 2018-2022 for
label: BODY

text: implementing United Nations Security Council Resolution
label: BODY

text: (UNSCR) 1325 on women, peace, and security highlighted
label: BODY

text: its commitment to support women’s roles in peacebuild-
label: BODY

text: ing and security. 2
label: BODY

text: While these frameworks provide a strong foundation, they
label: BODY

text: have not directly alleviated discrimination and inequalities
label: BODY

text: for women in Tunisia. Various factors including regional
label: BODY

text: instability and the COVID-19 pandemic have exacerbated
label: BODY

text: inequalities, poverty and discrimination for women and
label: BODY

text: girls. Primary challenges for women include: harmful
label: BODY

text: social norms that remain embedded in institutions and
label: BODY

text: legal frameworks; high unemployment, especially for
label: BODY

text: young women; increasing incidence of both economic
label: BODY

text: and political violence, including online; despite parity laws,
label: BODY

text: low rates of women in governance; and the rising tide of
label: BODY

text: violent extremism.
label: BODY

text: UN WOMEN’S CONTRIBUTIONS
label: H2

text: Since 2009, UN Women has contributed to progress on
label: BODY

text: issues of equality and women’s empowerment in Tunisia.
label: BODY

text: Its integration into the national UN Country Team (UNCT)
label: BODY

text: in 2019 allowed it to deepen its support to women’s issues
label: BODY

text: in Tunisia across its triple mandate.
label: BODY

text: Despite challenges, UN Women has led groundbreaking
label: BODY

text: research on issues such as women’s political participa-
label: BODY

text: tion and parity, which underlies its normative work . The
label: BODY

text: results from this research stand ready to support updates
label: BODY

text: to the legal framework. In its coordination efforts, UN
label: BODY

text: Women consolidated a strong gender perspective in
label: BODY

text: the most recently approved United Nations Sustainable
label: BODY

text: Development Cooperation Framework (UNSDCF), which
label: BODY

text: guides the UN system’s efforts through 2025. UN Women’s
label: BODY

text: direct support to women’s groups and national institutions
label: BODY

text: made possible the initial implementation of the National
label: BODY

text: Observatory on EVAW. To increase economic empower-
label: BODY

text: ment and improve social cohesion, UN Women built up
label: BODY

text: the expertise of local ministries and civil society groups on
label: BODY

text: gender norms, security and women’s employment oppor-
label: BODY

text: tunities. UN Women advanced women’s political participa-
label: BODY

text: tion and leadership by sharpening its expertise on issues
label: BODY

text: related to women, elections and the electoral process.
label: BODY

text: UN WOMEN STRATEGIC NOTE: A roadmap to gender equality
label: H3

text: The Strategic Note (SN) articulates the multi-year strategy, rationale, envisioned results, targets, and resource require-
label: BODY

text: ments for a UN Women Office. In essence, the SN provides a roadmap for improving the lives of women and girls in the
label: BODY

text: context where UN Women operates. It is developed in consultation with key partners and in alignment with the United
label: BODY

text: Nations Sustainable Development Cooperation Framework, UN Women’s Strategic Plan and key national, regional, and
label: BODY

text: global gender equality priorities. SNs are funded by a combination of core and non-core resources.
label: BODY

text: UN Women’s SN is similar to a Country Programme Document (CPD) used by other UN entities.
label: BODY

text: To learn more about the work and results of UN Women Tunisia, visit our Transparency Portal .
label: BODY

text: UN WOMEN’S COMPARATIVE ADVANTAGE
label: BODY

text: UN Women’s comparative advantage in Tunisia is centred
label: BODY

text: around the expertise it brings to the UNCT on gender
label: BODY

text: equality and its agility to form and maintain partner-
label: BODY

text: ships across a range of women’s groups in the midst of a
label: BODY

text: changing socio-political context. UN Women Tunisia works
label: BODY

text: across diverse dimensions of civil society, academia, and
label: BODY

text: both local and national-level government. As it contin-
label: BODY

text: ues to build relationships of trust with women and lead-
label: BODY

text: ers across all regions of Tunisia, UN Women leverages its
label: BODY

text: convening role to facilitate women’s participation and
label: BODY

text: capacity building. For instance, UN Women’s role as a
label: BODY

text: convener has allowed civil society organizations (CSOs)
label: BODY

text: to collaborate to address economic violence, now explicitly
label: BODY

text: recognized under Tunisian law. Its comparative advantage
label: BODY

text: vis-à-vis UN partners lies in its complementary approach,
label: BODY

text: which avoids duplication and builds on complementary
label: BODY

text: strengths of each agency. For instance, UN Women’s role
label: BODY

text: in supporting those left furthest behind ensures that
label: BODY

text: programming in Tunisia considers these groups, such as
label: BODY

text: rural women, women with disabilities and women in the
label: BODY

text: informal economy, with a special focus on the care econ-
label: BODY

text: omy. UN Women takes a leading role regarding economic
label: BODY

text: violence while supporting the service aspect on EVAW
label: BODY

text: under the leadership of the UN Population Fund (UNFPA).

text: PRIORITY RESULT 1:
label: H2

text: Women’s equal access to economic opportunities and
label: H3

text: decent work
label: H3

text: This priority responds to key structural factors underly-
label: BODY

text: ing economic inequalities, including the lack of the right
label: BODY

text: of inheritance, unpaid care work, and lack of access to
label: BODY

text: credit and land ownership. These factors perpetuate
label: BODY

text: gender disparities and hinder women’s entrepreneurial
label: BODY

text: and economic potential. UN Women will focus on bolster-
label: BODY

text: ing income security for the most vulnerable women in
label: BODY

text: Tunisia by supporting national efforts to address economic
label: BODY

text: violence and evidence-based economic reforms that
label: BODY

text: increase women’s participation in the labour force. This
label: BODY

text: will include supporting women’s transition from the
label: BODY

text: informal to the formal sector. To accomplish this, UN
label: BODY

text: Women proposes a large-scale economic empowerment
label: BODY

text: programme tailored to high-priority groups, including
label: BODY

text: rural women, educated youth who are unemployed and
label: BODY

text: women with disabilities. The programme is structured
label: BODY

text: around three pillars: policy reforms to counteract struc-
label: BODY

text: tural barriers; initiatives to address economic violence
label: BODY

text: and stereotypes; and building skills and facilitating access
label: BODY

text: to employment for women in rural and urban areas by
label: BODY

text: addressing issues such as lack of safe transportation,
label: BODY

text: low-quality childcare and unsafe workplaces. The latter
label: BODY

text: component incorporates the strengthening of gender-re-
label: BODY

text: sponsive budgeting.
label: BODY

text: PARTNERS
label: BODY

text: A joint programme on rural women’s economic empower-
label: BODY

text: ment, currently under way, brings together the cross-cut-
label: BODY

text: ting expertise of several UN partners, including the
label: BODY

text: World Food Programme (WFP), the Food and Agriculture
label: BODY

text: Organization (FAO) and the International Fund for
label: BODY

text: Agricultural Development (IFAD). On the issue of youth
label: BODY

text: employment, UN Women is engaging the private sector
label: BODY

text: both nationally and locally. Long-standing partnerships
label: BODY

text: with CSOs, women’s rights groups, and international part-
label: BODY

text: ners such as the Government of Canada are the mainstay
label: BODY

text: for UN Women’s emerging work on economic violence and
label: BODY

text: combating harmful social norms and stereotypes.

text: Tunisia, until 2022, had a strong legal framework for gender
label: BODY

text: equality, including temporary special measures to promote
label: BODY

text: women’s political participation. With those quotas in
label: BODY

text: place, the main focus of this programme was to improve
label: BODY

text: implementation. However, given the recent legislative
label: BODY

text: changes, the focus now becomes two-fold: to support new
label: BODY

text: legislation with the target of parity and then to support
label: BODY

text: implementation through targeted technical support and
label: BODY

text: capacity building of potential and elected women lead-
label: BODY

text: ers. Technical support will focus on enhancing represen-
label: BODY

text: tation in electoral and political processes, specifically on
label: BODY

text: candidate nomination and voter registration. It will also
label: BODY

text: aim to strengthen gender-responsive legislation, policies
label: BODY

text: and specifically gender-responsive budgeting, which will
label: BODY

text: improve access to services and keep institutions account-
label: BODY

text: able. Through policy advocacy, based on a solid founda-
label: BODY

text: tion of gender-specific statistics, UN Women will leverage
label: BODY

text: partner support to collect that data and to build policy
label: BODY

text: according to that evidence. Finally, the capacity-building
label: BODY

text: efforts will first aim to expand the pool of potential new
label: BODY

text: leaders to include diverse and capable women political
label: BODY

text: leaders, and then to strengthen their know-how around
label: BODY

text: running for election and addressing barriers – including
label: BODY

text: potential violence – that might hinder their participation.
label: BODY

text: PARTNERS
label: BODY

text: To address women’s political empowerment, cooperation
label: BODY

text: with a range of partners is essential. This includes civil
label: BODY

text: society and women’s rights groups linked to emerging
label: BODY

text: leaders at the local and national level. To address poli-
label: BODY

text: cies and improve inclusion, UN Women will collaborate
label: BODY

text: with the media to ensure coherent advocacy. Improving
label: BODY

text: gender-disaggregated statistics requires engaging criti-
label: BODY

text: cal partners such as the National Observatory on EVAW
label: BODY

text: and the National Institute of Statistics in addition to
label: BODY

text: the Ministry of Finance and the National School of
label: BODY

text: Administration.
label: BODY

text: PRIORITY RESULT 3:
label: H2

text: Women’s participation for inclusive peacebuilding and
label: H3

text: reconciliation
label: H3

text: Tunisia took a major step for gender equality when it
label: BODY

text: embarked on its first NAP to implement its commitment
label: BODY

text: to engage girls and women in inclusive peacebuilding. The
label: BODY

text: aim is to promote stability, contribute to the elimination
label: BODY

text: of all forms of violence and gender-based discrimination
label: BODY

text: and build resilience in the face of risks, conflicts, extrem-
label: BODY

text: ism and terrorism, as outlined in UNSCR 1325. As the first
label: BODY

text: NAP concluded in 2022, UN Women has helped oversee
label: BODY

text: the evaluation of the first NAP to identify a more targeted
label: BODY

text: approach to support the engagement of women in peace
label: BODY

text: and security processes during the NAP’s second phase.
label: BODY

text: Consequently, UN Women will strengthen the NAP II’s
label: BODY

text: monitoring framework and engage key stakeholders for
label: BODY

text: their effective advocacy and participation. UN Women
label: BODY

text: will improve capacities of the institutions responsible
label: BODY

text: for monitoring the NAP and will engage CSOs to over-
label: BODY

text: see its development and implementation. UN Women
label: BODY

text: will continue to support the judiciary for a gender-sensi-
label: BODY

text: tive interpretation and application of the law to protect
label: BODY

text: women’s rights, particularly in the context of transitional
label: BODY

text: justice and cybercriminality. To address the recurring
label: BODY

text: violent extremism and terrorism that has increased since
label: BODY

text: 2011, UN Women will also support national reform efforts
label: BODY

text: to address roots of vulnerability including prevention of
label: BODY

text: terrorism and violent extremism, and rehabilitation and
label: BODY

text: reintegration for victims and survivors.
label: BODY

text: PARTNERS
label: H3

text: A range of partners is necessary to build bridges across
label: BODY

text: institutions for inclusive peacebuilding. Thus, UN
label: BODY

text: Women will work with government institutions includ-
label: BODY

text: ing the Ministry of Women, Family, and the Elderly, and
label: BODY

text: a broad range of CSOs and women’s groups. It will also
label: BODY

text: continue to support the NAP’s Steering Committee and
label: BODY

text: work jointly with the Committee on the monitoring of
label: BODY

text: the NAP. Coordination across UN and international part-
label: BODY

text: ners is facilitated by UN Women’s initiative with Canada
label: BODY

text: to establish the Gender Development Group (GDG). The
label: BODY

text: GDG has chosen to focus on three primary issues, includ-
label: BODY

text: ing advancing inclusive peacebuilding around UNSCR 1325.
label: BODY

text: BECOMING A FUNDING PARTNER
label: H3

text: Achieving the Sustainable Development Goals
label: BODY

text: by 2030 calls for transformative, collabora-
label: BODY

text: tive action. Strategic, innovative, and efficient
label: BODY

text: funding partnerships are essential to realize
label: BODY

text: UN Women’s vision of a gender-equal world,
label: BODY

text: articulated in the SN.
label: BODY

text: HOW CAN FUNDING PARTNERS
label: H3

text: ENGAGE WITH UN WOMEN’S SN?
label: H3

text: Partners may provide SN direct funding , which
label: BODY

text: is softly earmarked by geography (regional or
label: BODY

text: lytic; they enable UN Women to choose the
label: BODY

text: highest-impact use of the funds in the country
label: BODY

text: in which it operates. SN funding is also predict-
label: BODY

text: able , as commitments are often made for the
label: BODY

text: full SN time span, better enabling transforma-
label: BODY

text: tive results for women and girls.
label: BODY

text: Importantly, SN direct funds strengthen
label: BODY

text: UN Women’s ability to respond to emerging
label: BODY

text: needs in response to unforeseen contextual
label: BODY

text: changes, including humanitarian needs (e.g.,
label: BODY

text: to prioritize the safety of women and girls in
label: BODY

text: a crisis or in response to the adverse effects of
label: BODY

text: natural disasters).
label: BODY

text: Furthermore, these funds can be reallocated
label: BODY

text: when emerging evidence suggests a new
label: BODY

text: approach is needed to produce the desired
label: BODY

text: result more efficiently or effectively. They can
label: BODY

text: be used for diverse types of costs and can
label: BODY

text: therefore draw funds to areas that are often
label: BODY

text: unfunded—yet crucial—such as advocacy for
label: BODY

text: behavioural change, UN coordination, etc.,
label: BODY

text: supporting the organization’s effectiveness.
label: BODY

text: Funding partners may also provide project
label: BODY

text: funding , which is tightly earmarked for a
label: BODY

text: specific project or initiative in the SN. These
label: BODY

text: funds are not flexible. Reporting on the use of
label: BODY

text: such funds is done against the specific project
label: BODY

text: but not against the full SN.
label: BODY

text: SN funding represents an ambitious, targeted,
label: BODY

text: and smart investment in gender equality and
label: BODY

text: women’s empowerment.

text: GIRLS, UN WOMEN WAS ESTABLISHED TO

label: BODY

text: UN Women supports UN Member States as they set global
label: BODY

text: standards for achieving gender equality, and works with
label: BODY

text: governments and civil society to design laws, policies,
label: BODY

text: programmes and services needed to ensure that the standards
label: BODY

text: are effectively implemented and truly benefit women and girls
label: BODY

text: worldwide. It works globally to make the vision of the Sustainable
label: BODY

text: Development Goals a reality for women and girls and stands
label: BODY

text: behind women’s equal participation in all aspects of life, focusing
label: BODY

text: on four strategic priorities: Women lead, participate in and benefit
label: BODY

text: equally from governance systems; Women have income security,
label: BODY

text: decent work and economic autonomy; All women and girls live a
label: BODY

text: life free from all forms of violence; Women and girls contribute
label: BODY

text: to and have greater influence in building sustainable peace and
label: BODY

text: resilience, and benefit equally from the prevention of natural
label: BODY

text: disasters and conflicts and humanitarian action. UN Women also
label: BODY

text: coordinates and promotes the UN system’s work in advancing
label: BODY

text: gender equality.
